{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567327"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:59:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:59:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18961"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18961"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.09,0.77,0.02,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11695"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80633"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11695"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18961"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65925"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5699"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11402"},{"type":"tags","id":"11403"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27515"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27516"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80633"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 92-year-old woman with advanced metastatic breast cancer, severe dementia, and multiple organ failure is admitted to hospital with septic shock. She has no advance care directive. Her family insists on full intensive care treatment, including mechanical ventilation and dialysis, despite the medical team\u0027s assessment that such interventions would be futile.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the ethical approach to managing futile treatment requests?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Seek legal intervention to override family wishes","Escalate care while arranging ethics consultation","Provide balanced information and engage in shared decision-making","Document family disagreement and withdraw treatment","Continue treatment until consensus is reached"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct approach is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eprovide balanced information and engage in shared decision-making\u003C/strong\u003E. This involves explaining the clinical situation, likely outcomes, and reasons why certain interventions would be futile, while maintaining respectful dialogue with the family and acknowledging their emotional needs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect approaches are problematic because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeek legal intervention to override family wishes\u003C/strong\u003E - This prematurely escalates the situation and may damage therapeutic relationships before attempting proper communication\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEscalate care while arranging ethics consultation\u003C/strong\u003E - This delays appropriate decision-making and may cause harm through potentially inappropriate interventions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDocument family disagreement and withdraw treatment\u003C/strong\u003E - This fails to adequately engage with the family or attempt to reach consensus through proper communication\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue treatment until consensus is reached\u003C/strong\u003E - This may result in prolonged inappropriate care and suffering while avoiding necessary difficult decisions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe goal is to reach a consensus through respectful communication, while maintaining professional integrity and acting in the patient\u0027s best interests. This may include involving ethics consultation, palliative care, or other support services.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditionally, various legislation exists in Australia, highlighting that \u0027a health practitioner is not required to offer futile or non-beneficial treatment.\u0027 This is important to remember if shared decision-making fails or a family will not change their mind and medical treatment is not clinically indicated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Medical futility refers to interventions that are unlikely to produce meaningful benefit for the patient.","Decisions about futile treatment should consider clinical evidence, quality of life, and patient values/preferences.","Healthcare providers have an ethical obligation to avoid providing futile treatments that may cause harm or suffering."],"references":["Australian Government. Advance care directive. [online]. 2024. [Cited 2025 Jan 21]. Available at: https://www.health.gov.au/topics/palliative-care/planning-your-palliative-care/advance-care-direc...","Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx","https://www.publicadvocate.vic.gov.au/resource/72-end-of-life-decision-making-when-there-is-no-family-or-medical-treatment-decision-maker/file#:~:text=As%20indicated%20above%2C%20a%20health,futile%20or%20non%2Dbeneficial%20treatment.\u0026text=then%20the%20health%20practitioner%20asks,or%20refuse%20the%20proposed%20treatment."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65925"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18961"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65925"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-21T21:53:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-21T22:39:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11695"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80633"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4943"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"cre